On the basis of the type and strength of intermolecular interactions and molecular mechanics/Monte Carlo free energy simulations studies of a number of structurally similar compounds, it has been proposed that, the most stable host–guest complexes in aqueous solution are those with the strongest intermolecular interactions such as ion-dipole and hydrophobic interactions.

For this system, the best binders should be those with all or most of the following characteristics:
1. An ammonium group to produce an ion-dipole interaction with the carboxylate anion portals;
2. A trimethyl or tetramethylammonium group to interact with the aromatic electron cloud of pillar[6]arene and therefore it produces a cation-π interaction;
3. Longer alkyl chain to produce hydrophobic interactions on both side of the cavity;

Bearing the mechanism of action of carboxylate pillar[6]arene in mind, Guest molecule A is an excellent binder to being binding with an ammonium group.

<answer>A</answer>
